# Frontend & UI Rules

## General
- Use React Server Components by default. Add `'use client'` only when the component needs interactivity (event handlers, hooks, browser APIs).
- Use Tailwind CSS for all styling. No CSS modules, no styled-components, no inline style objects.
- Mobile-first responsive design. Start with the mobile layout, then add `md:` and `lg:` breakpoints.
- Keep components focused. One component, one job. If a component file exceeds 150 lines, split it.

## Dashboard (Venue Staff)
- Located in `src/app/dashboard/`.
- Requires authentication. Use middleware to redirect unauthenticated users.
- Real-time updates via Supabase Realtime subscriptions.
- **Connection status indicator:** Always show a visible banner when the WebSocket drops. Auto-enable 30-second polling fallback. Banner clears on reconnection.
- Day sheet is the priority view. Optimise for readability at arm's length on a tablet mounted at a host stand.
- Dietary flags and allergy warnings must use colour coding that is impossible to miss. Red for severe allergies.

## Booking Pages (Guest-Facing)
- Located in `src/app/book/[venue-slug]/`.
- Public - no authentication required.
- Must be fast. Target < 2 second load time on mobile.
- Booking flow: date → time slot/sitting → party size → guest details → dietary/occasion → deposit payment → confirmation.
- Show cancellation policy clearly before payment.
- Stripe payment uses Stripe Elements (Stripe's own iFrame) - never a custom card input.

## iFrame Widget
- Same booking flow as the hosted page, rendered for iFrame embedding.
- Uses `postMessage` API for parent page communication with origin validation.
- Accent colour customisable via URL parameter.
- Must work inside third-party websites with varying CSP policies.

## Confirm-or-Cancel Page
- Located at a public URL like `/confirm/[booking-token]`.
- Shows: venue name, booking date/time, party size, dietary notes.
- Two clear buttons: "Confirm I'm Coming" (green/teal) and "Cancel My Booking" (red/muted).
- Cancel flows to a secondary confirmation showing deposit implications.
- Must be fully functional on mobile. Most guests will tap this from an SMS link.

## Day Sheet Specific
- Chronological order by booking time.
- Each row: time, guest name, party size, table (if assigned), dietary flags, occasion, deposit status, confirmation status.
- Allergy flags displayed prominently with colour coding.
- One-tap check-in (mark as Arrived).
- No-show button only available after the venue's configured grace period has elapsed.
- If offline fallback is implemented: service worker caches last state, queues check-in actions, syncs on reconnection.

## Accessibility
- All interactive elements must be keyboard accessible.
- Use semantic HTML: `<button>` for actions, `<a>` for navigation, `<form>` for forms.
- Colour is not the only indicator - use icons or text alongside colour coding.
- Form inputs must have associated labels.

## Loading and Error States
- Every data-fetching component must handle three states: loading, error, and success.
- Use skeleton loaders, not spinners, for content areas.
- Error states must be actionable: show what went wrong and offer a retry.
